Das Gespenst der Armut: “Das Bettelweib von Locarno” — Zwischen traditioneller christlicher, kantisch aufgeklärter und moderner marxistischer Auffassung -- t13: The Problem of Knowledge and the Discourse of the Hysteric: Exploring a Lacanian Interpretation of “Die Marquise von O. . .” -- t14: Religion nach der Aufklärung: Die Heilige Cäcilie — Identität, Religion und Moderne -- t15: Breaking Skulls: Kleist, Hegel, and the Force of Assertion -- t16: Kleist’s “Übermarionette” and Schrenck-Notzing’s “Traumtänzerin”: Nervous Mechanics and Hypnotic Performance under Modernism -- t17: Falling after the Fall: The Analysis of the Infinite in Kleist’s Marionette Theater -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNew essays employing a multitude of approaches to the works of Kleist, in the process shedding light on our present modernity.Modernity, according to some views, poses the problem of homo politicus -- the problem of how to act in a moral universe without a "master narrative," without a final foundation. From this angle, the oeuvre of Heinrich vonKleist -- novellas, dramas, and essays -- addresses problems emerging from a new universe of Kantian provenance, in many ways the same universe we inhabit today. This volume of new essays investigates Kleist's position in ourever-changing conception of modernity, employing aesthetic, narrative, philosophical, biographical, political, economic, anthropological, psychological, and cultural approaches and wrestling with the difficulties of historicizingKleist's life and work. Central questions are: To what extent can the multitude of breaking points and turning points, endgames and pre-games, ruptures and departures that permeate Kleist's work and biography be conceptually bundled together and linked to the emerging paradigm of modernity? And to what extent does such an approach to Kleist not only advance understanding of this major German writer and his work, but also shed light on the nature of our present modernity? Contributors: Seán Allan, Peter Barton, Hilda Meldrum Brown, David Chisholm, Andreas Gailus, Bernhard Greiner, Jeffrey L. High, Anette Horn, Peter Horn, Wolf Kittler, Jonathan W. Marshall, Christian Moser, Dorothea von Mücke, Nancy Nobile, David Pan, Ricarda Schmidt, Helmut J. Schneider. Bernd Fischer is Professor of German at the Ohio State University. Tim Mehigan is Professor of German in the Department of Languagesand Cultures at the University of Otago, New Zealand.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aModernism (Literature). 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aGerman Literature. 4aPhilosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aHeinrich von Kleist.  aKleist's position.  aaesthetic.  aanthropological.  abiographical.  acultural approaches.  aeconomic.  ahistorical context.  amodernity.  amoral universe.  anarrative.  aphilosophical.  apolitical.  apsychological.1 aAllan, Seán, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarton, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Hilda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChisholm, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChisholm-Univ. of Arizona, Dr. David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, Bernd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, Bernd, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGailus, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreiner, Bernhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHigh, Jeffrey L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo